            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1888-10-17T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1888-10-17T00:00:00-05:00" n="346" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d346">
                <head>No. 346.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Reinberg</persName> to Mr. <persName type="to">Rives</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Consulate-General, of the United States</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Guayaquil</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1888-10-17">
                            <hi rend="italic">October</hi> 17, 1888</date>. (Received November
                        14.)</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 161.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have to inform the Department that a decree has
                    been passed by the last Ecuadorian Congress, to take effect from January 1,
                    1889, allowing vessels flying foreign flags to engage in the river and coasting
                    trade of Ecuador. This was formerly allowed only to vessels flying the national
                    flag, the Government reserving the right to stop all traffic and close any or
                    all ports during a time of revolution or in the event of a war with any foreign
                    nation.</p>
                <p>I have, etc.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Martin Reinberg</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Vice-Consul General.</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
